data.content:
Yes! Two better options depending on your needs:

**1. `[DataRow]` — simplest for constant values:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**2. Typed tuples via `DynamicData` — when you need computed/non-constant data:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Why these are better than `object[]`:**

| | `object[]` | `DataRow` | Typed tuples |
|---|---|---|---|
| Type safety | ❌ Runtime casts | ✅ Compile-time | ✅ Compile-time |
| Inline | ❌ Separate property | ✅ On method | ❌ Separate property |
| Non-constants | ✅ | ❌ Constants only | ✅ |

Use `[DataRow]` when all values are compile-time constants (the common case). Use typed tuples when you need computed values, complex objects, or shared data across tests.
